# Fitter pipeline

Fitting a diagram turns a set of region sizes into concrete shapes —
circles, ellipses, squares, or rectangles — whose overlaps reproduce
those sizes as closely as possible. Eunoia runs this in four stages.

## 1. Initial layout (MDS)

An initial arrangement is computed with **positional multidimensional
scaling**. Each shape's size is fixed up front from the requested set
areas, and only the centre `(x, y)` of every shape is solved for.
Target pairwise distances come from inverting each shape's own overlap
formula, so the warm start already places overlapping sets near each
other and disjoint sets apart.

## 2. Optimizer encoding

The MDS positions are converted into the per-shape parameter encoding
the optimiser works in — an ellipse, for example, is optimised over
`[x, y, ln a, ln b, φ]` rather than its raw semi-axes. The log encoding
keeps widths and heights positive and balances the scales of the
parameters so a single solver setting works across positions, radii,
and angles.

## 3. Final optimisation

The shape parameters are refined by **minimising a loss** that measures
the discrepancy between the fitted region areas and the requested ones.
The optimiser and the loss are both selectable; circles and ellipses
use analytical gradients where the loss allows, and a global-escape
stage can kick in when a plain local solve stalls on a hard layout.

## 4. Normalisation

The fitted layout is post-processed for a stable, consistent
appearance: disconnected clusters are separated, the diagram is rotated
to a canonical orientation, centred, and the clusters are packed
together. The result is a layout you can polygonise, label, and render.

How faithfully the result reproduces the requested sizes is summarised
by a few scalar metrics — see [Goodness of fit](/docs/concepts/goodness-of-fit/).

For the authoritative details — optimisers, losses, gradients, and the
shape-specific encodings — see the
[Architecture section in `AGENTS.md`](https://github.com/jolars/eunoia/blob/main/AGENTS.md).
